    "Thomas G. Long": "Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`' baptism is the prototype for our baptisms. In this story of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`' baptism we find an anticipation of all\nsubsequent Christian baptisms done in the name of the Trinity. Though it would be a mistake to think of Matthew\nteaching elaborate trinitarian theology (the doctrine of the Trinity was fully developed only after the New Testament\nperiod), we do see in the story of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`' baptism a depiction of all three persons of the Trinity in relationship. At the\nclose of the Gospel of Matthew, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` sends his disciples out to the nations to baptize \"in the name of the Father and of\n[v_Mat_28_19] the Son and of the Holy Spirit\" (Matt. 28:19), and here, at the beginning of Matthew, we see the prototype of that\nbaptism: Father, Son, and Spirit gathered together in the event of baptism.\n< previous page\npage_34\nnext page >\nfile:///D|/Gigapedia/Bible%20Studies/0664252575__gigle.ws/0664252575/files/page_34.html2010-11-7 6:27:27\npage_35\n< previous page\npage_35\nnext page >\nPage 35\nJesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Is Put to the Test\n[v_Mat_4_1] Matthew 4:1 11\n4:1 Then Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` was led up by the Spirit into the wilderness to be tempted by the devil. 2 He fasted forty days\nand forty nights, and afterwards he was famished. 3 The tempter came and said to him, \"If you are the Son of\nGod, command these stones to become loaves of bread.\" 4 But he answered, \"It is written,\n'One does not live by bread alone,\nbut by every word that comes from the mouth of God.'\"\n5 Then the devil took him to the holy city and placed him on the pinnacle of the temple, 6 saying to him, \"If\nyou are the Son of God, throw yourself down; for it is written,\n'He will command his angels concerning you,'\nand 'On their hands they will bear you up,\nso that you will not dash your foot against a stone.'\"\n7 Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` said to him, \"Again it is written, 'Do not put the Lord your God to the test.'\"\n8 Again, the devil took him to a very high mountain and showed him all the kingdoms of the world and their\nsplendor; 9 and he said to him, \"All these I will give you, if you will fall down and worship me.\" 10 Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` said\nto him,\n\"Away with you, Satan! for it is written,\n'Worship the Lord your God,\nand serve only him.'\"\n11 Then the devil left him, and suddenly angels came and waited on him.\nAs soon as Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`' identity is announced, this identity is immediately put to the test. Here, in the opening verses of",
    "Walter Brueggemann, Warren Carter": "THE NARRATIVE CONTEXT OF i : 2 i :\nJESUS' ORIGINS\nFollowing the genealogy, the immediate narrative context of 1:21 concerns\nJesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`' origin (1:18 yeveaiQ, genesis). His conception occurs \"before (Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`\nand Mary `[char_Mary_Ref]`) came together\" and results \"from the holy spirit.\" It is God's\nact and initiative. Conception by a god was typical of outstanding imperial\nfigures like Alexander (Plutarch, Alex. 2.1-3.4), Rome's founder Romulus\n(Plutarch, Rom. 2.3-6) and the emperor Augustus (Suetonius, Aug. 94.4).\nIt identifies them as agents chosen by the gods to do their will. Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` is set in\nsuch elect and commissioned political company, but with the key difference:\nGod elects him to accomplish God's saving purposes.\n3. In 4:8 Satan of\u00ad\nfers Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` \"all the kingdoms/empires (PocciiAeiac,, basileia) of the world.\"\nThe offer reveals Satan's control of the world and its political realms. If\nSatan controls the world's empires, it follows that the leading empire, Rome,\nis under the devil's control and is, in the Gospel's perspective, the devil's\nagent. Rome's rule manifests Satan's empire. The noun pocciAeioc (\"kingdom/\nempire\") in 4:8 recalls the use of pccciAetic, (basileus) for Rome's ally, King\nHerod, in 2:1, linking him to Satan, and reinforcing a contrast with King\nJesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` (2:2, PaoiAevcJ and his God-given empire (4:17, PaoiAeicx).\n3. A critical-constructive stance is appropriate when the powers that be\nare attempting to achieve justice.\nBasic to the Pilgrim-Strieter paradigm is the practice of discernment or being\ncritical. Discerning the power's commitment to a just society, discerning its\nconcern with who benefits and who is harmed, and discerning whether it is\n\"bent on serious mischief or self-assertion\"\n5 determines the appropriate re\u00ad\nsponse. The \"critical-constructive stance\" sees a partnership between ruling\npowers and communities of faith for the common good or just treatment of\nall. It is essentially a subordinationist approach in which faith communities\nrecognize governments as doing the will of God.\n3. J. Rufus Fears, \"Cult of Jupiter,\" 7-9."
